    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-02-24T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-02-24T08:00:00-05:00" n="170"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d170">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1501</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-02-24T14:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 24, 1915, 2 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received February 25, 9 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1680. Referring to your propositions in identic note.<note n="1" xml:id="d170fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_119">p. 119</ref>.</note> From
                    private information think Germany inclined to accept but will probably want raw
                    material to enter as well as food for civil population. Copper may be subject of
                    contention but there is ample copper here for war purposes and it is only needed
                    for manufactures. There will also be objection to agents of American Government
                    superintending food distribution as this might involve some surrender of
                    sovereignty but this can be obviated by creation of an American commission or
                    something of sort similar to Belgian or one proposed for Poland and of which I
                    could be chairman personally and not officially.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
